      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34958,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Higher bacterial count at stationary phase in enrichment medium.&nbsp;</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></span></strong></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Enrichment media </strong>are <strong>designed to promote the growth of a particular group of microorganisms </strong>by providing <strong>essential nutrients and environmental conditions favorable for their growth</strong>. As a result, <strong>bacteria grown in an enrichment medium </strong>typically <strong>reach a higher bacterial count </strong>at the <strong>stationary phase compared to those grown in a standard medium</strong>. This is because the <strong>enriched environment supports a more extensive proliferation of bacteria </strong>before they <strong>exhaust the available nutrients </strong>and <strong>reach the stationary phase</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/07/screenshot-2024-03-04-122639.jpg\" style=\"height:345px; width:400px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/07/screenshot-2024-03-04-122705.jpg\" style=\"height:379px; width:1000px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>A.</strong> <strong>Faster lag phase in enrichment medium </strong>is <strong>not </strong>necessarily <strong>true</strong>, as the <strong>lag phase is a period of adaptation </strong>and <strong>does not always correlate with the richness of the medium</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>B.</strong> <strong>Slower log phase </strong>in the enrichment medium is <strong>incorrect</strong>, as <strong>enrichment media </strong>are designed to <strong>facilitate</strong>, <strong>not hinder</strong>, <strong>bacterial growth</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>D.</strong> <strong>Earlier death phase </strong>in the enrichment medium is also <strong>incorrect. </strong>The <strong>death phase </strong>is determined by <strong>factors like nutrient depletion and waste accumulation</strong>, which are not directly influenced by the enrichment of the medium.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Enhanced bacterial growth </strong>in <strong>enrichment media compared to standard media </strong>is <strong>vital in microbiological studies</strong>. <strong>Bacteria like E. coli</strong>, when <strong>grown in enrichment media</strong>, demonstrate a <strong>higher bacterial count at the stationary phase </strong>due to the <strong>provision of essential nutrients </strong>and favorable growth conditions.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Apurva Sastry Essentials of Microbiology, pg 23/4e</span></span></strong></p>",
